						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ok, I am not sure how valid this will be once the new changes go live since the death of kiting, but I thought I would share with you all my current strategy for keeping my character able to solo heroics on the same ( and sometimes up to a couple higher) levels as him.
<br />

<br />
Good kiting techniques need to be a given, but the kiting is just the execution, it is the tactical aspect of the game.  The moment of glory.  The moment that everything prior in the game led up to.  That is how I feel in each of my solo fights.  I am alwasy trying to get just a little bit mroe daring, cut it a little closer, fight the mob that will just about kill me but that I should be able to take.
<br />

<br />
So I will not focus on kiting, especially since the topic has been convered in depth and they are effectively removing it from the game.  Instead I will talk about all the exists as beneath it, that which makes it happen and determines the outcome: the charahter.
<br />

<br />
Having a l33t  scout means playing three games.  One is the money game, two is the adventure game, three is the crafting game.  These games all inter-relate and support each other.
<br />

<br />
The most important basic game is the money game.  This game is a necessary evil (unless you have a high level char which can support you on your climb, boring) and it needs to be played agressively.  The essence of this game is taking a modest amount of capital and converting it into stacks of platinum.  At level 28 my total sales is in the 30 platinum range.  
<br />

<br />
The essence of this game is buy low, sell high.  TO do this you must keep a float.  Keep money around, but dont spend it frivolsously.  You need to watch, you need to learn what items are popular, how fast they sell, what they sell for and whether the one currently on the market is worthi buying for resale.  Ideal for this is the technique I call "the greedy bastard"  This involves watching the market for a few particular items that you know about and always buying them if you can make a good margin on them..  Margins are sliding scale, An expensive item you would only buy if you new the margin was goood and it had decent salability.  The majority of my money was made in the book selling business (ie the artisans and scholars and recently the apothocaries) and the precious metals and adepts from my class.
<br />

<br />
If done right this should provide enough of an income to always buy th etop of the line armor/weapons/etc for your adventure level.  This in turn allows you to head out and because you have the best possibel equipment, allows for a moderatly playable solo game.  You can try challanges because you have good equipment.   This means more exp earned per fight and also higher calibre treasure.  Money makes money.
<br />

<br />
Sumplementing this is your tradeskill.  This is your wild card.  It can be used in a pinch to make extra money to suplement your sales (or if you are devouted to the right field it can really boost sales) or it can be used to privide some aspect of cutting edge item for adventuring.  My thinking of late is that by far the best class for a socut is the alchemist.  The alchemist is awesome because not only can you produce our own potions and poisons (which are necesary to make you top of the lin in adventuring) but the alchemist can pull in lotsa dollars as well if necessary.  Out of all the tradespeople I hire, my alchemist manages to drain me for the most bucks, and I am always returning.  Not only that, if you look at some of the higher level posions or potions on the servers, they are selling in the 20 gold range.  Not bad when you consider that something that people are going to use up constantly will bring you that kind of return...  I typically use up about 3 bottles pers session, if I were higher level that might amount to as much as 60 gold per session from one player!  
<br />

<br />
See why you might want to be that class?  Not only can you provide yourself with oodles of niceness you can sell it for stacks of platinum.  Sure it is nice to make bows and such but really, the reagents are expensive, they sell moderatly slow and you only ever need to make yourself one.  Thus there is little incentive to keep tradskilling.  Besides that you can always find someone who will turn your reagent into whatever you want for cheap.  It is the poisons you will be constantly burning through.  Nonetheless any tradskill can work in this area, and realisitcally it is possible to skip tradskilling all toghether and just play the money-adventure aspect.  Or you could play any combination of the the three, but in my oppinion when you play all three together they support each other and make for a very potent and enjoyable game.  Now if only I could switch my class to alchemist!!!!</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
						</tr>
					</table></td>
